{
  "What is the main difference between mechanical and chemical weathering?": "",
  "Mechanical weathering only occurs in cold climates": "",
  "Mechanical weathering breaks rock physically while chemical weathering changes its mineral composition": "",
  "Chemical weathering is faster than mechanical weathering in all environments": "",
  "Chemical weathering only occurs underground": "",
  "Mechanical weathering breaks rock into smaller pieces without altering its chemical composition, while chemical weathering transforms minerals through chemical reactions, creating entirely new substances.": "",
  "Frost wedging is most effective in climates where:": "",
  "It is always below freezing year-round": "",
  "It never freezes": "",
  "Rainfall is extremely heavy but temperatures stay warm": "",
  "Temperatures frequently cycle above and below freezing": "",
  "Frost wedging requires repeated freeze-thaw cycles so that water can enter cracks, freeze and expand by about 9%, then thaw and penetrate deeper with each cycle.": "",
  "Chemical weathering occurs fastest in which type of climate?": "",
  "Cold and dry": "",
  "Hot and dry": "",
  "Warm and wet": "",
  "Cold and wet": "",
  "Heat speeds up chemical reactions and water serves as both a reactant and a medium for dissolved chemicals, so warm, wet climates produce the fastest rates of chemical weathering.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of mechanical weathering?": "",
  "Tree roots growing into rock cracks and splitting the rock apart": "",
  "Iron minerals rusting on a rock surface": "",
  "Limestone dissolving in acidic water": "",
  "Feldspar converting to clay minerals": "",
  "Root wedging is a form of mechanical (physical) weathering because the growing roots physically pry the rock apart without changing its chemical composition.": "",
  "Oxidation in weathering is most similar to which everyday process?": "",
  "Blowing sand off a table": "",
  "Rusting of iron": "",
  "Freezing water in a tray": "",
  "Melting an ice cube": "",
  "Oxidation occurs when iron-bearing minerals in rock react with oxygen and water to produce iron oxide (rust), which is the same chemical process that causes metal tools and structures to rust.": "",
  "How does weathering differ from erosion?": "",
  "Erosion only occurs in deserts while weathering occurs everywhere": "",
  "Weathering breaks down rock in place without moving it, while erosion transports the material": "",
  "Weathering involves transport of material while erosion does not": "",
  "Weathering requires glaciers while erosion requires wind": "",
  "Weathering is the in-place breakdown of rock by physical or chemical means, while erosion is the transport of those weathered fragments to a new location by agents such as water, wind, ice, or gravity.": "",
  "Carbonation is responsible for creating which type of landscape?": "",
  "Volcanic plateaus": "",
  "Sand dune fields": "",
  "Glacial moraines": "",
  "Karst landscapes with caves and sinkholes": "",
  "Carbonic acid, formed when carbon dioxide dissolves in rainwater, slowly dissolves limestone over thousands to millions of years, creating caves, sinkholes, and other karst features.": "",
  "Which factor increases the overall rate of weathering?": "",
  "Covering the rock with a waterproof seal": "",
  "Increasing the exposed surface area of the rock": "",
  "Moving the rock to a cold, dry environment": "",
  "Decreasing the surface area of the rock": "",
  "Greater surface area exposes more of the rock to weathering agents such as water, air, and organisms, which accelerates both mechanical and chemical weathering processes.": "",
  "What is the first step in soil formation?": "",
  "Weathering of bedrock into sediment": "",
  "Metamorphism of existing rock": "",
  "Deposition of glacial till": "",
  "Volcanic eruption": "",
  "Weathering breaks bedrock into smaller fragments that form the mineral component of soil, making it the essential first step in soil formation before organic matter accumulates.": "",
  "Acid rain from pollution accelerates chemical weathering of which materials?": "",
  "Only igneous rocks like granite and basalt": "",
  "Only plant roots and vegetation": "",
  "Buildings, monuments, and natural rock, especially marble and limestone": "",
  "Only metals and alloys used in construction": "",
  "Acid rain contains sulfuric and nitric acids from industrial pollution, which react readily with carbonate minerals in marble and limestone, dissolving them much faster than natural rainwater.": "",
  "What is frost wedging?": "",
  "The chemical dissolution of limestone by carbonic acid": "",
  "The process of wind carving grooves into rock surfaces": "",
  "The melting of glacial ice that polishes rock surfaces": "",
  "The process by which water seeps into rock cracks, freezes, expands, and forces the crack wider over repeated cycles": "",
  "Frost wedging is a mechanical weathering process in which water enters cracks in rock, freezes and expands by approximately 9%, and gradually widens the crack with each freeze-thaw cycle until the rock splits apart.": "",
  "What is exfoliation in the context of weathering?": "",
  "The growth of lichen on rock surfaces": "",
  "The peeling away of rock in sheets when overlying pressure is removed, causing the rock to expand": "",
  "A type of chemical weathering caused by acid rain": "",
  "The transport of sediment by flowing water": "",
  "Exfoliation, also called unloading, occurs when overlying rock is eroded away, reducing confining pressure and causing the exposed rock below to expand and crack in concentric sheets, much like layers peeling off an onion.": "",
  "What is oxidation in the context of rock weathering?": "",
  "The physical grinding of rock by glacial movement": "",
  "The accumulation of salt crystals in rock pores": "",
  "The freezing of water inside rock fractures": "",
  "A chemical reaction in which iron-bearing minerals react with oxygen and water to form iron oxide": "",
  "Oxidation is a chemical weathering process in which iron in minerals reacts with oxygen and water to produce iron oxide (rust), weakening the rock structure and giving it a characteristic reddish-brown color.": "",
  "What is carbonic acid and how does it form?": "",
  "A byproduct of salt crystal growth in rock pores": "",
  "A strong industrial acid produced in factories": "",
  "A weak acid formed when carbon dioxide dissolves in rainwater": "",
  "An acid produced exclusively by volcanic eruptions": "",
  "Carbonic acid (H2CO3) forms naturally when carbon dioxide in the atmosphere dissolves in rainwater, creating a weak acid that is particularly effective at dissolving carbonate rocks like limestone.": "",
  "What does the term 'biological weathering' mean?": "",
  "The chemical alteration of rock by volcanic gases": "",
  "Weathering caused exclusively by bacteria in soil": "",
  "The breakdown of rock caused by living organisms such as plant roots, burrowing animals, lichens, and bacteria": "",
  "The formation of fossils within sedimentary rock": "",
  "Biological weathering encompasses all the ways living organisms break down rock, including root wedging by plants, burrowing by animals, acid production by lichens, and mineral decomposition by bacteria.": "",
  "What is karst topography?": "",
  "A landscape formed by the chemical dissolution of soluble rocks like limestone, featuring caves, sinkholes, and underground drainage": "",
  "A flat plain created by river deposition": "",
  "A volcanic landscape with lava tubes and craters": "",
  "A landscape shaped primarily by glacial erosion": "",
  "Karst topography develops when carbonic acid in groundwater dissolves soluble bedrock such as limestone over long periods, creating distinctive features including caves, sinkholes, disappearing streams, and underground rivers.": "",
  "What does 'hydrolysis' mean in the context of chemical weathering?": "",
  "The evaporation of water from rock surfaces": "",
  "A chemical reaction between water and minerals that breaks down silicate minerals like feldspar into clay": "",
  "The freezing of water inside rock cracks": "",
  "The physical force of water flowing over rock surfaces": "",
  "Hydrolysis is a chemical weathering reaction in which water molecules react with silicate minerals, breaking their crystal structures and transforming minerals like feldspar into softer clay minerals.": "",
  "What is the 'angle of repose' as it relates to weathered material?": "",
  "The depth below which weathering no longer occurs": "",
  "The rate at which chemical weathering progresses per year": "",
  "The temperature at which rock begins to chemically weather": "",
  "The steepest angle at which a pile of loose, weathered material can remain stable without sliding": "",
  "The angle of repose is the maximum slope angle at which loose granular material such as sand, gravel, or weathered rock fragments can rest without sliding, and it varies depending on particle size, shape, and moisture content.": "",
  "What is salt crystal growth (haloclasty) in weathering?": "",
  "A chemical reaction between salt and iron minerals": "",
  "The dissolving of salt deposits by rainwater": "",
  "The mechanical weathering process where salt crystals grow in rock pores and exert pressure that breaks the rock apart": "",
  "The formation of salt flats by evaporation of lake water": "",
  "Salt crystal growth is a mechanical weathering process common in arid and coastal environments where saltwater seeps into rock pores, evaporates, and leaves behind growing salt crystals that exert enough pressure to fracture the rock.": "",
  "What does 'differential weathering' mean?": "",
  "Weathering that occurs at different rates on different types or areas of rock, creating uneven landforms": "",
  "Weathering that occurs only during certain seasons": "",
  "Weathering caused by the difference between day and night temperatures": "",
  "The difference between weathering and erosion rates": "",
  "Differential weathering occurs because some rocks or minerals resist weathering better than others, causing softer rock to erode faster and leaving behind harder, more resistant rock as prominent features like hoodoos and arches.": "",
  "A geologist notices that a granite monument in a humid, subtropical city has its feldspar crystals turning into a soft, chalky substance while the quartz crystals remain intact. Which weathering process best explains this observation?": "",
  "Hydrolysis is chemically converting the feldspar to clay while quartz resists chemical attack": "",
  "Frost wedging is breaking apart both minerals equally": "",
  "Oxidation is rusting the feldspar while leaving quartz untouched": "",
  "Exfoliation is peeling off the feldspar layers only": "",
  "Feldspar is highly susceptible to hydrolysis, which chemically breaks it down into clay minerals, while quartz is extremely resistant to chemical weathering due to its strong silicon-oxygen bonds, explaining the differential deterioration.": "",
  "A homeowner in Minnesota notices that the concrete steps leading to her house develop new cracks every spring. The cracks grow wider each year. What weathering process is most likely responsible?": "",
  "Chemical weathering from acid rain dissolving the concrete": "",
  "Oxidation from iron rebar rusting inside the concrete": "",
  "Biological weathering from tree roots pushing against the steps": "",
  "Frost wedging from repeated freeze-thaw cycles during winter and spring": "",
  "In Minnesota's climate, water enters tiny cracks in the concrete during thaw periods, then freezes and expands during cold snaps, gradually widening the cracks through repeated freeze-thaw cycles throughout winter and early spring.": "",
  "Explorers visiting a cave system in Kentucky notice stalactites hanging from the ceiling and stalagmites growing from the floor. What weathering process created this cave system?": "",
  "Exfoliation from pressure release as overlying rock was removed": "",
  "Mechanical weathering by underground rivers physically carving through the rock": "",
  "Chemical weathering by carbonic acid dissolving the limestone over millions of years": "",
  "Biological weathering by burrowing organisms tunneling through the rock": "",
  "Kentucky's cave systems formed as slightly acidic groundwater (containing carbonic acid from dissolved CO2) slowly dissolved the limestone bedrock over millions of years, and the stalactites and stalagmites formed as dissolved minerals re-precipitated from dripping water.": "",
  "A park ranger in Yosemite observes large, curved sheets of granite peeling away from the surface of Half Dome. What type of weathering is this an example of?": "",
  "Frost wedging from ice forming in surface cracks": "",
  "Root wedging from trees growing on the rock face": "",
  "Exfoliation caused by the release of confining pressure as overlying rock eroded away": "",
  "Chemical weathering by oxidation": "",
  "Half Dome's iconic shape is partly due to exfoliation, where the removal of overlying rock reduces pressure on the granite below, causing it to expand and crack in curved, concentric sheets that peel away from the surface.": "",
  "A farmer in a tropical region notices that the granite boulders in his field are deeply weathered into reddish-brown soil, while similar granite boulders in his cousin's field in northern Canada are mostly intact with only surface cracks. What best explains this difference?": "",
  "Wind erosion is stronger in tropical regions": "",
  "The tropical climate's heat and abundant moisture accelerate chemical weathering far more than the cold, dry Canadian climate": "",
  "The Canadian granite is a harder variety of the mineral": "",
  "The tropical boulders are older than the Canadian ones": "",
  "Warm temperatures speed up chemical reactions and abundant rainfall provides the water needed for chemical weathering processes like hydrolysis and oxidation, so tropical environments weather rock much faster than cold, dry climates.": "",
  "An archaeologist discovers that ancient marble statues displayed outdoors in an industrial city have lost their facial features and fine details, while identical statues stored indoors remain perfectly preserved. What is the most likely cause?": "",
  "Frost wedging from winter ice formation": "",
  "Acid rain from industrial pollution dissolving the marble's calcium carbonate": "",
  "Root wedging from nearby trees": "",
  "Wind abrasion wearing down the stone surfaces": "",
  "Marble is composed of calcium carbonate, which readily dissolves when exposed to acid rain containing sulfuric and nitric acids from industrial emissions, gradually eroding fine details from outdoor statues while indoor statues remain protected.": "",
  "A construction crew building a highway through a mountainous region cuts into a hillside and exposes fresh rock. Over the next few years, they notice the exposed rock face crumbling faster than the surrounding undisturbed rock. What explains this accelerated weathering?": "",
  "The construction equipment chemically altered the rock": "",
  "The exhaust fumes from passing vehicles dissolve the rock": "",
  "Cutting the hillside exposed fresh, unweathered rock to weathering agents and increased the surface area available for attack": "",
  "Highway traffic vibrations cause the rock to disintegrate": "",
  "Exposing fresh rock dramatically increases the surface area available for weathering agents to attack, and the newly exposed rock has not yet developed a protective weathering rind, making it much more vulnerable to both mechanical and chemical breakdown.": "",
  "A coastal community in the Middle East notices that the sandstone buildings near the shore are crumbling and flaking apart, even though there is very little rain. A white, crusty substance is visible in the rock pores. What weathering process is most likely at work?": "",
  "Biological weathering from desert organisms": "",
  "Carbonation from dissolved CO2 in the air": "",
  "Salt crystal growth from seawater evaporating in the rock pores": "",
  "Frost wedging from nighttime temperature drops": "",
  "In coastal arid environments, salt-laden sea spray or groundwater seeps into porous rock, and as the water evaporates, salt crystals grow within the pores and exert enough pressure to fracture and crumble the rock from within.": "",
  "A student observes a large tree growing on top of a rocky hillside. The tree's roots have visibly pushed apart a large boulder into two halves. At the same time, the student notices the rock surfaces around the roots have a greenish tint from lichen growth. Which types of weathering are occurring simultaneously?": "",
  "Only mechanical weathering from the roots": "",
  "Neither mechanical nor chemical weathering, only erosion": "",
  "Both mechanical weathering from root wedging and chemical weathering from acids produced by the lichen": "",
  "Only chemical weathering from the lichen": "",
  "This scenario demonstrates how mechanical and chemical weathering often work together: the tree roots physically pry the rock apart (mechanical), while lichens produce weak acids that chemically dissolve minerals on the rock surface (chemical).": "",
  "A geologist studying a riverbed in the Appalachian Mountains finds that the pebbles are all well-rounded, while boulders on the nearby hillside are angular with sharp edges. She also notices the pebbles are composed mainly of quartz, while the hillside boulders contain feldspar, mica, and quartz. What does this evidence tell her about the weathering and transport history?": "",
  "The river pebbles were rounded by abrasion during transport, and only quartz survived because feldspar and mica were destroyed by chemical weathering": "",
  "The pebbles and boulders come from completely different rock types": "",
  "The boulders are younger than the pebbles": "",
  "The river sorted the pebbles by color rather than by mineral resistance": "",
  "As rock fragments travel downstream, abrasion rounds their edges (mechanical weathering), and chemical weathering breaks down less resistant minerals like feldspar and mica, leaving behind only the highly resistant quartz, demonstrating how both weathering types work together over time.": ""
}